00:00:25.788 --> 00:00:27.830
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Let's
move on to our next module

00:00:27.830 --> 00:00:30.080
of the day, which called
People: The Heart of Lean.

00:00:33.670 --> 00:00:35.350
What people who
have studied Lean

00:00:35.350 --> 00:00:39.190
and the Toyota production
system in general have found

00:00:39.190 --> 00:00:41.050
is that there's
two major aspects

00:00:41.050 --> 00:00:42.500
of these kinds of systems.

00:00:42.500 --> 00:00:45.010
One is this kind of
just-in-time production

00:00:45.010 --> 00:00:47.170
that we typically see,
and which we talked about

00:00:47.170 --> 00:00:48.970
in the new balance plant tour.

00:00:48.970 --> 00:00:50.770
But the second and
equally important

00:00:50.770 --> 00:00:52.600
component of these
kinds of systems

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:55.600
is the respect-for-human
system that exists.

00:00:55.600 --> 00:00:58.060
And you heard, again in
our new balance plant tour

00:00:58.060 --> 00:01:00.663
you heard Claudio talk
about the immense respect

00:01:00.663 --> 00:01:02.080
that they have for
their employees

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:05.230
and how employee involvement
is valued and encouraged

00:01:05.230 --> 00:01:08.800
in his organization.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:11.120
Now the trouble is
for a lot of folks,

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:15.090
and engineers in particular, is
we think about the people part

00:01:15.090 --> 00:01:16.640
to the problem and
we sometimes sees

00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:18.257
these as really challenging.

00:01:18.257 --> 00:01:20.590
And this is a quote from a
gentleman at Northrop Grumman

00:01:20.590 --> 00:01:22.173
who's fairly high
in their management,

00:01:22.173 --> 00:01:25.660
and he sums it up very nicely
by saying "the soft stuff is

00:01:25.660 --> 00:01:26.885
the hard stuff."

00:01:26.885 --> 00:01:29.260
The soft stuff, which is
usually thought of as the people

00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:31.540
issues, is often seen
as some of the hardest

00:01:31.540 --> 00:01:32.920
challenges in an organization.

00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:34.210
He's very true.

00:01:34.210 --> 00:01:36.160
But it's one of
those important items

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:41.290
to work on when you think about
making an organization lean.

00:01:41.290 --> 00:01:43.990
So in this section
on people we want

00:01:43.990 --> 00:01:46.510
to have you achieve the
following three learning

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:47.750
objectives.

00:01:47.750 --> 00:01:49.240
The first is to
be able to explain

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:54.350
why people are key to improving
productivity and organization.

00:01:54.350 --> 00:01:56.350
The second is to
make you realize

00:01:56.350 --> 00:01:59.710
that effective communication,
shared goals, and knowledge,

00:01:59.710 --> 00:02:03.010
and mutual respect lead
to improved organizational

00:02:03.010 --> 00:02:04.570
performance.

00:02:04.570 --> 00:02:07.150
And third, we'd like you
to be able to participate

00:02:07.150 --> 00:02:09.190
as a member of a team
in order to achieve

00:02:09.190 --> 00:02:11.060
a productive and
positive outcome.

00:02:11.060 --> 00:02:13.065
So to get us kicked
off on this discussion,

00:02:13.065 --> 00:02:14.440
I'd like you to
think and reflect

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:17.920
on the most important things
that contribute to your job

00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:18.778
satisfaction.

00:02:18.778 --> 00:02:21.070
So whether you're a student
or whether you're currently

00:02:21.070 --> 00:02:25.120
working, think about what it is
that makes you very satisfied

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:26.770
with your job.

00:02:26.770 --> 00:02:29.680
And I'd like to ask
for some volunteers

00:02:29.680 --> 00:02:32.197
to tell me first of all, what's
the most important thing?

00:02:32.197 --> 00:02:33.280
Let's start off with that.

00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:35.238
I'm going to start to
make a list on the board.

00:02:36.734 --> 00:02:38.942
AUDIENCE: Maybe feeling like
you've made a difference

00:02:38.942 --> 00:02:40.379
at the end of the day.

00:02:40.379 --> 00:02:42.534
Whether it be to the
customers or to the staff

00:02:42.534 --> 00:02:44.211
that you work with.

00:02:44.211 --> 00:02:45.650
ANNALISA WEIGEL: What else?

00:02:45.650 --> 00:02:46.398
Yes.

00:02:46.398 --> 00:02:48.190
AUDIENCE: Felt like
I've learned something.

00:02:48.190 --> 00:02:51.957
OK, I've going to
put something up.

00:02:51.957 --> 00:02:53.040
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Learning.

00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:54.840
Great.

00:02:54.840 --> 00:02:56.590
AUDIENCE: Having control
over the outcomes

00:02:56.590 --> 00:02:57.548
you're responsible for.

00:03:01.984 --> 00:03:02.976
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Yes.

00:03:02.976 --> 00:03:05.460
AUDIENCE: I'd say having
room for creativity.

00:03:05.460 --> 00:03:07.280
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Creativity.

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:08.540
In the back.

00:03:08.540 --> 00:03:11.414
AUDIENCE: Feeling
respected or valued.

00:03:11.414 --> 00:03:12.820
ANNALISA WEIGEL: What else?

00:03:12.820 --> 00:03:13.760
Yes.

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:15.650
AUDIENCE: Making
connections with individuals

00:03:15.650 --> 00:03:17.793
and the community at large.

00:03:17.793 --> 00:03:18.960
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Connection.

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:21.890
So it's the relationships with
your co-workers, customers,

00:03:21.890 --> 00:03:23.380
everybody?

00:03:23.380 --> 00:03:25.640
AUDIENCE: Yeah, with my
patients and med students

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:28.280
that I work with, but also
connecting with the needs

00:03:28.280 --> 00:03:31.030
of the community in general.

00:03:31.030 --> 00:03:33.970
I guess with my colleagues, too.

00:03:33.970 --> 00:03:35.440
Though that seems secondary.

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:36.910
ANNALISA WEIGEL: What else?

00:03:36.910 --> 00:03:37.890
Yes?

00:03:37.890 --> 00:03:39.850
AUDIENCE: Acknowledgement
of a job well done.

00:03:42.790 --> 00:03:44.260
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Yes?

00:03:44.260 --> 00:03:48.180
AUDIENCE: I think a job you can
work to your full potential.

00:03:48.180 --> 00:03:50.140
ANNALISA WEIGEL: OK.

00:03:50.140 --> 00:03:52.010
Anything else?

00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:53.344
AUDIENCE: Responsibility.

00:03:56.463 --> 00:03:57.296
ANNALISA WEIGEL: OK.

00:03:57.296 --> 00:03:57.796
In the back.

00:03:57.796 --> 00:03:58.910
Yes.

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:01.725
AUDIENCE: I don't require that,
but the financial incentives.

00:04:01.725 --> 00:04:03.600
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Financial
incentive, salary?

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:04.225
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:04:04.225 --> 00:04:05.020
Make money.

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:06.853
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Let's
call that what it is.

00:04:06.853 --> 00:04:07.620
Salary.

00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:08.260
Great.

00:04:08.260 --> 00:04:09.740
We've all got to eat.

00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:10.310
Go ahead.

00:04:10.310 --> 00:04:13.058
AUDIENCE: Having the time to
do my job right the first time

00:04:13.058 --> 00:04:14.600
and feeling like I
didn't wallow away

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:17.760
in errors throughout the day.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:19.690
ANNALISA WEIGEL:
So adequate time.

00:04:19.690 --> 00:04:20.200
What else?

00:04:23.310 --> 00:04:24.930
AUDIENCE: Working hours.

00:04:24.930 --> 00:04:27.180
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Your hours.

00:04:27.180 --> 00:04:30.180
So take a look at the
list we have here.

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:32.640
And think if the most important
thing that contributes

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:35.405
to your own job satisfaction
isn't on this list,

00:04:35.405 --> 00:04:36.780
and you'd like to
raise your hand

00:04:36.780 --> 00:04:38.010
and tell us about
it, that'll be great.

00:04:38.010 --> 00:04:39.268
we'll add it to the list.

00:04:39.268 --> 00:04:41.060
Otherwise we might
start to winnow it down.

00:04:41.060 --> 00:04:43.032
AUDIENCE: Lack of stress.

00:04:43.032 --> 00:04:44.740
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Stress
free environment.

00:04:44.740 --> 00:04:47.490
AUDIENCE: Or reduced stress.

00:04:47.490 --> 00:04:49.100
ANNALISA WEIGEL:
OK, so low stress.

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:51.350
Reduced stress.

00:04:51.350 --> 00:04:52.180
Susan?

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:54.678
AUDIENCE: Being part of a team.

00:04:54.678 --> 00:04:56.043
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Yes, in back.

00:04:56.043 --> 00:04:57.710
AUDIENCE: It's sort
of related to hours,

00:04:57.710 --> 00:04:58.775
but work-family balance.

00:05:03.036 --> 00:05:04.729
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Yes.

00:05:04.729 --> 00:05:05.521
AUDIENCE: Feedback.

00:05:06.162 --> 00:05:08.670
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Feedback
from your supervisor?

00:05:11.150 --> 00:05:11.650
OK.

00:05:11.650 --> 00:05:12.240
Great.

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:14.920
Do we have any-- one more
burning last suggestion?

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:15.440
Matteis?

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:16.357
AUDIENCE: Environment.

00:05:16.357 --> 00:05:18.648
Working environment.

00:05:18.648 --> 00:05:20.690
ANNALISA WEIGEL: OK, so
take a read through these

00:05:20.690 --> 00:05:23.300
and what I'd like
to ask you to do now

00:05:23.300 --> 00:05:26.960
is each person take a voting
strip of dots they should

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:29.120
be distributed on your table.

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:30.800
What I'll ask you to
do is just come up

00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:35.640
to the board and place one dot
next to each of your top three

00:05:35.640 --> 00:05:36.140
