00:07:31.520 --> 00:07:32.810
We also talked about that.

00:07:32.810 --> 00:07:34.520
Someone made that suggestion.

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:38.090
These are all things that
have a much higher correlation

00:07:38.090 --> 00:07:41.870
with having high performance
work environment than things

00:07:41.870 --> 00:07:43.200
on this side.

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:47.000
And notice pay is sort of
farthest from people's job

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:48.343
satisfaction.

00:07:48.343 --> 00:07:49.760
So it just really
goes to show you

00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:52.093
it's not just what you pay
people and then job security.

00:07:52.093 --> 00:07:55.220
But it's a lot of these
other important satisfaction

00:07:55.220 --> 00:08:01.383
items that contributes to people
really doing a productive job.

00:08:01.383 --> 00:08:03.050
Now there are several
different theories

00:08:03.050 --> 00:08:04.820
about how workers
are productive.

00:08:04.820 --> 00:08:07.280
They relate to the brainstorming
that we've been doing.

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:09.127
The first is usually
called Theory X

00:08:09.127 --> 00:08:11.210
and it was one of the
original management theories

00:08:11.210 --> 00:08:14.060
and it's based on the premise
that workers don't like to work

00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:15.780
so they must be made to work.

00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:18.680
So you have to enforce harsh
rules and lots of motivation

00:08:18.680 --> 00:08:21.710
to get them to overcome
this general human desire

00:08:21.710 --> 00:08:23.900
to not work.

00:08:23.900 --> 00:08:24.580
Yes?

00:08:24.580 --> 00:08:26.420
AUDIENCE: I have a thought.

00:08:26.420 --> 00:08:28.970
As you got salary
and paid, I think

00:08:28.970 --> 00:08:34.299
why this one might
be a bit different

00:08:34.299 --> 00:08:36.740
is because on the
average, I guess

00:08:36.740 --> 00:08:39.950
that the bulk of the workers
are already paid good enough

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:43.370
to take care of themselves and
their families and all of that.

00:08:43.370 --> 00:08:46.420
So if you're paying someone
a salary that is not

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:52.310
able to take care of himself,
or not able to pay his bills,

00:08:52.310 --> 00:08:56.280
I don't think it
won't be an issue.

00:08:56.280 --> 00:08:59.350
I think that this might
not be a very good example,

00:08:59.350 --> 00:09:02.730
because if we look at the
average pay and the lowest pay

00:09:02.730 --> 00:09:04.923
they get, it might be
something very tangible.

00:09:04.923 --> 00:09:05.840
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Sure.

00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:07.400
And I think I would
agree with you.

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:09.950
That's a function of
some base level of pay.

00:09:09.950 --> 00:09:13.640
And perhaps one of the reasons
why salary sometimes shows up

00:09:13.640 --> 00:09:15.950
in this environment is
more important than on some

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:17.420
of these other surveys
that have been done

00:09:17.420 --> 00:09:19.760
is because we have a number of
students in the room, right.

00:09:19.760 --> 00:09:21.260
Raise your hand if
you're a student.

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:23.720
If you're not being
paid much of anything.

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:25.940
And hence, if salary is
really important to you.

00:09:25.940 --> 00:09:28.730
But as you suggest, when
you go out in the workforce

00:09:28.730 --> 00:09:31.580
and you are earning a
salary and putting food

00:09:31.580 --> 00:09:34.100
on the table is not
as concerning for you

00:09:34.100 --> 00:09:36.560
as it might be when you're not
getting salary as a student,

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:39.175
some of these other items
really become important.

00:09:39.175 --> 00:09:40.550
So after a while
if you're trying

00:09:40.550 --> 00:09:42.920
to create a high performing
work organization,

00:09:42.920 --> 00:09:45.380
it's not so much
increasing people's pay

00:09:45.380 --> 00:09:47.360
as it is focusing on
making sure there are

00:09:47.360 --> 00:09:48.950
all of these other conditions.

00:09:48.950 --> 00:09:52.100
And sometimes people think it's
easier to just pay people more

00:09:52.100 --> 00:09:55.060
and that doing this is harder
but it pays off much higher.

00:09:57.960 --> 00:09:59.710
All right, so back to
our worker theories,

00:09:59.710 --> 00:10:02.090
which comes into play a bit
with your comment as well.

00:10:02.090 --> 00:10:03.910
So we started at early
management theory

00:10:03.910 --> 00:10:06.130
with Theory X. So
then to counter

00:10:06.130 --> 00:10:08.530
that after a little while
of experimenting with it

00:10:08.530 --> 00:10:10.570
they really came upon
Theory Y, which is

00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:12.790
reflected in Elton Mayo's work.

00:10:12.790 --> 00:10:15.040
Where they said, no,
actually workers--

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:16.780
if you just make them
happy then they're

00:10:16.780 --> 00:10:18.080
going to be really productive.

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:20.050
So this theory out
of that was born

00:10:20.050 --> 00:10:22.150
the whole focus
on human resources

00:10:22.150 --> 00:10:24.190
and human relations
in the workplace

00:10:24.190 --> 00:10:27.050
and trying to create
a happy workplace.

00:10:27.050 --> 00:10:29.380
So that was about 1920,
and then around the turn

00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:32.110
of this century,
we have expressed

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:35.020
by Dick Kleine at John
Deere, his thought

00:10:35.020 --> 00:10:38.630
is that a productive
worker is a happy worker.

00:10:38.630 --> 00:10:41.380
So we've got these three
different competing theories.

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:43.450
Of those three, which
do you think most aligns

00:10:43.450 --> 00:10:46.040
with a Lean way of thinking?

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:49.360
How many people think it's
the first theory, Theory X?

00:10:49.360 --> 00:10:52.000
How many people think
it's the middle one?

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.550
How many people think
it's the last one?

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:55.780
Very good.

00:10:55.780 --> 00:10:57.250
That's the way we think, too.

00:10:57.250 --> 00:10:59.920
We think that Dick
Kleine's thought

00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:01.480
about a productive
worker being happy

00:11:01.480 --> 00:11:06.070
worker really is the
way that things are.

00:11:06.070 --> 00:11:09.460
And to try to illustrate some
of the links between employee

00:11:09.460 --> 00:11:11.990
productivity and
company performance,

00:11:11.990 --> 00:11:14.998
we want to take a case study
here on Southwest Airlines.

