And just to give you some
brief background on Southwest

00:11:17.290 --> 00:11:19.780
as a company and
put them in context,

00:11:19.780 --> 00:11:21.072
they are one of the best--

00:11:21.072 --> 00:11:22.780
well they really are
the best performance

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:24.820
of the major US
domestic airlines.

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:29.590
And you can see their
profitability metric here

00:11:29.590 --> 00:11:30.250
on the chart.

00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:33.160
Southwest is in blue, which
is far above the red, which

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:35.290
is an aggregate of all the
major domestic airlines

00:11:35.290 --> 00:11:39.490
and their profitability over
the past couple of decades.

00:11:39.490 --> 00:11:42.340
And in addition, Southwest
has made an operating profit

00:11:42.340 --> 00:11:44.600
every year for over 30 years.

00:11:44.600 --> 00:11:47.140
Now this is a big
achievement for an airline.

00:11:47.140 --> 00:11:49.870
No one else has this record and
many, many times, many years,

00:11:49.870 --> 00:11:52.510
many airlines are at a net loss.

00:11:52.510 --> 00:11:54.250
A few more items
about Southwest,

00:11:54.250 --> 00:11:57.340
they are one of the
safest airlines around.

00:11:57.340 --> 00:11:59.080
They did have a very
homogeneous fleet

00:11:59.080 --> 00:12:00.968
until they merged
with AirTran, and that

00:12:00.968 --> 00:12:03.010
simplifies some of their
training and maintenance

00:12:03.010 --> 00:12:04.650
and logistics items.

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:06.700
They have never laid
off any employees

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:09.520
even after the events of 9/11.

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:12.310
They are the most highly
unionized US airline,

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:13.810
even though there's
some perceptions

00:12:13.810 --> 00:12:15.790
out there that there's
no unions on Southwest.

00:12:15.790 --> 00:12:17.440
Because, after all,
those Southwest employees

00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:19.607
are so happy and the company
is doing so good surely

00:12:19.607 --> 00:12:20.710
they don't have unions.

00:12:20.710 --> 00:12:22.000
That's not true at all.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.560
They're highly unionized they
have a point-to-point, which

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:29.333
is different than a
hub-and-spoke route structure.

00:12:29.333 --> 00:12:31.000
And many of the other
airlines in the US

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.010
operate on a hub-and-spoke
route structure.

00:12:33.010 --> 00:12:34.552
You can think of it
a little bit more

00:12:34.552 --> 00:12:37.920
like a batch and cue
and continuous flow.

00:12:37.920 --> 00:12:39.990
A little bit different.

00:12:39.990 --> 00:12:41.740
They consistently offer
some of the lowest

00:12:41.740 --> 00:12:43.180
fares that are around.

00:12:43.180 --> 00:12:45.940
They're liked by investors
and employees and customers,

00:12:45.940 --> 00:12:47.010
I should say.

00:12:47.010 --> 00:12:49.000
And so you might ask
what makes Southwest

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.220
so successful in its business.

00:12:51.220 --> 00:12:54.250
And Professor Jody Hoffer
Gittell in her book

00:12:54.250 --> 00:12:57.070
The Southwest Airlines Way
which resulted out of her PhD

00:12:57.070 --> 00:12:59.170
work here at MIT,
she argues it's

00:12:59.170 --> 00:13:03.990
because of Southwest's
organizational competency.

00:13:03.990 --> 00:13:07.600
And it's characterized by
shared goals, shared knowledge,

00:13:07.600 --> 00:13:09.910
and mutual respect.

00:13:09.910 --> 00:13:15.070
And she calls these three
things relational coordination.

00:13:15.070 --> 00:13:18.760
And she says that shared goals
helps the employees to align

00:13:18.760 --> 00:13:20.590
and prioritize
the organization's

00:13:20.590 --> 00:13:25.610
success over doing their job or
succeeding at just their job.

00:13:25.610 --> 00:13:27.670
The second item of
relational coordination

00:13:27.670 --> 00:13:30.080
is this element of
shared knowledge.

00:13:30.080 --> 00:13:32.140
So if everybody has the
same kind of knowledge,

00:13:32.140 --> 00:13:35.110
then you have visibility
of the overall work process

00:13:35.110 --> 00:13:36.610
and not just your
little part on it.

00:13:36.610 --> 00:13:39.027
So you can help see the linkages
between what you're doing

00:13:39.027 --> 00:13:40.660
and what someone
else is doing and be

00:13:40.660 --> 00:13:45.170
able to create overall a more
efficient and effective system.

00:13:45.170 --> 00:13:47.950
And lastly, this third element
of relational coordination

00:13:47.950 --> 00:13:49.440
is mutual respect.

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:52.990
And that helps to reduce some
of the barriers between employee

00:13:52.990 --> 00:13:55.570
groups and helps them
cooperate more effectively

00:13:55.570 --> 00:13:57.628
to get the job done.

00:13:57.628 --> 00:13:59.920
And all these three elements
of relational coordination

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:01.510
really couldn't
happen if it weren't

00:14:01.510 --> 00:14:05.570
for the underlying practice
of effective communication.

00:14:05.570 --> 00:14:08.410
This effective communication
is particularly

00:14:08.410 --> 00:14:11.080
one where people are
communicating about the problem

00:14:11.080 --> 00:14:14.380
itself and not really
worried about assigning blame

00:14:14.380 --> 00:14:15.790
when something bad goes wrong.

00:14:15.790 --> 00:14:18.550
So if you think in your
own work environment,

00:14:18.550 --> 00:14:20.530
you may be able to
think about some people

00:14:20.530 --> 00:14:22.300
that you interact
with perhaps who

00:14:22.300 --> 00:14:24.340
are very good at thinking
just about the problem

00:14:24.340 --> 00:14:26.257
and trying to separate
the people out from it.

00:14:26.257 --> 00:14:28.120
And then you may
also know some people

00:14:28.120 --> 00:14:31.060
who tend to focus more on
blaming somebody when something

00:14:31.060 --> 00:14:34.043
goes wrong and not really
focusing on what went wrong

00:14:34.043 --> 00:14:34.960
and how we can fix it.

00:14:34.960 --> 00:14:37.300
But really who might
be responsible for it.

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:40.780
That's not as effective
communication as we could be.

00:14:40.780 --> 00:14:43.150
Other elements of what makes
communication effective?

00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:47.170
Frequent, timely, open, honest.

00:14:47.170 --> 00:14:49.270
Very, very simple description.

00:14:49.270 --> 00:14:53.710
Not as easy to achieve, but very
simple to try to understand.

00:14:56.660 --> 00:14:58.940
Now when an organization
has very high

00:14:58.940 --> 00:15:01.520
relational coordination,
professor Hoffer Gittell

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:04.850
found that high levels of
relational coordination

00:15:04.850 --> 00:15:07.388
do correlate with
performance for the airlines

00:15:07.388 --> 00:15:08.180
that she's studied.

00:15:08.180 --> 00:15:11.330
And this graph shows you
some composite measure

00:15:11.330 --> 00:15:12.410
of airline performance.

00:15:12.410 --> 00:15:14.700
On the x, she took many
different things into account,

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:18.080
including on time
departures, fewer

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:20.010
lost bags, things like that.

00:15:20.010 --> 00:15:22.100
And then she has
relational coordination as

00:15:22.100 --> 00:15:24.950
measured by another amalgam of
a bunch of different measures

00:15:24.950 --> 00:15:26.870
that she created
in her research.

00:15:26.870 --> 00:15:28.520
And each of these
dots is a number

00:15:28.520 --> 00:15:30.828
of different airlines
in different locations

00:15:30.828 --> 00:15:31.620
around the country.

00:15:31.620 --> 00:15:33.260
There are two here
shown from Southwest

00:15:33.260 --> 00:15:35.810
and the others are for three
other different airlines.

00:15:35.810 --> 00:15:37.190
But you see the general trend.

00:15:37.190 --> 00:15:39.410
As we increase
relational coordination

00:15:39.410 --> 00:15:42.590
we tend to see the aggregate
performance increase.

00:15:42.590 --> 00:15:45.710
So we've seen how relational
coordination works

00:15:45.710 --> 00:15:47.810
and increases
performance in airlines,

00:15:47.810 --> 00:15:49.700
but you can apply
this concept well

00:15:49.700 --> 00:15:51.530
beyond the domain of airlines.

00:15:51.530 --> 00:15:54.380
And it really applies, she
says, in any setting where

00:15:54.380 --> 00:15:56.670
there is task interdependence.

00:15:56.670 --> 00:15:59.090
So there may be hand-offs
that take place requiring

00:15:59.090 --> 00:16:00.885
feedback and iterations.

00:16:00.885 --> 00:16:02.510
Or where there is
uncertainty and there

00:16:02.510 --> 00:16:06.140
has to be continual adjustment
of plans and updating.

00:16:06.140 --> 00:16:08.180
Or where there are
time constraints,

00:16:08.180 --> 00:16:12.560
and so you can't just wait
while you try to fix a problem.

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:14.360
Now I want you to
think about what

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:17.390
you think of when your
careers are going to unfold

00:16:17.390 --> 00:16:20.018
and the kinds of industries
you all anticipate being in,

00:16:20.018 --> 00:16:21.560
and tell me if you
think you are ever

00:16:21.560 --> 00:16:24.110
going to spend your time in
an organization that does not

00:16:24.110 --> 00:16:27.410
have one or more of
these elements in it.

00:16:27.410 --> 00:16:28.078
I suspect not.

00:16:28.078 --> 00:16:29.870
I suspect you're all
going to find yourself

00:16:29.870 --> 00:16:32.330
in organizations where
these are critical elements.

00:16:32.330 --> 00:16:34.640
And so this notion of
relational coordination

00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:36.740
is one that would
translate equally well

00:16:36.740 --> 00:16:39.560
into any environment
where these items exist.

00:16:39.560 --> 00:16:42.920
So one example is
health care, obviously.

00:16:42.920 --> 00:16:46.520
Another one that we talk
about is product development.

00:16:46.520 --> 00:16:49.730
Product development is done by
different kinds of engineers,

00:16:49.730 --> 00:16:50.300
typically.

00:16:50.300 --> 00:16:51.063
Lots of hand-offs.

00:16:51.063 --> 00:16:51.980
Lots of uncertainties.

00:16:51.980 --> 00:16:53.510
Lots of time constraints.

00:16:53.510 --> 00:16:56.510
And I'm sure that you can
think of many other situations.

00:16:56.510 --> 00:16:57.530
Any come to mind?

00:17:00.770 --> 00:17:01.330
Yes, Fabrice.

00:17:01.330 --> 00:17:03.008
AUDIENCE: Government programs.

00:17:03.008 --> 00:17:04.800
Where the government
invests in an industry

00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:07.420
to develop something and all
of the sudden you have said,

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:09.605
and then everybody has
something different.

00:17:09.605 --> 00:17:10.730
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Excellent.

00:17:10.730 --> 00:17:11.230
Yeah.

00:17:11.230 --> 00:17:11.900
Great example.

00:17:11.900 --> 00:17:13.983
There's lots of different
products being developed

00:17:13.983 --> 00:17:15.670
under those circumstances.

00:17:15.670 --> 00:17:18.430
All right well let's look at one
particular example translating

00:17:18.430 --> 00:17:22.819
relational coordination into
another particular environment.

00:17:22.819 --> 00:17:26.119
Professor Hoffer Gittell
then went and said,

00:17:26.119 --> 00:17:28.030
well let me see if this
really does translate

00:17:28.030 --> 00:17:29.193
into other environments.

00:17:29.193 --> 00:17:31.360
And so she went and studied
health care environments

00:17:31.360 --> 00:17:34.270
to see if these same elements
of relational coordination

00:17:34.270 --> 00:17:36.400
correlated with
elements of performance.

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:38.220
And just as you saw
with the airline chart,

00:17:38.220 --> 00:17:40.720
the same kind of pattern starts
to appear in the health care

00:17:40.720 --> 00:17:42.100
industry here.

00:17:42.100 --> 00:17:45.250
So it's not only do we
suspect that this notion

00:17:45.250 --> 00:17:46.840
of relational
coordination translates.

00:17:46.840 --> 00:17:48.370
We actually have
yet another study

00:17:48.370 --> 00:17:50.230
in another domain,
which does show

00:17:50.230 --> 00:17:53.740
that we see increased levels
of performance with increased

00:17:53.740 --> 00:17:57.790
instances of relational
coordination.

00:17:57.790 --> 00:18:00.430
So in order to achieve
relational coordination,

00:18:00.430 --> 00:18:04.060
professor Hoffer Gittell looked
at various practices that were

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:05.830
in place at Southwest Airlines.

00:18:05.830 --> 00:18:09.010
And she identified and
codified 10 different ones

00:18:09.010 --> 00:18:12.670
that underlied being able to
create an environment where

00:18:12.670 --> 00:18:14.830
there was good relational
coordination, which

00:18:14.830 --> 00:18:17.845
then led to having very
good performance outcomes.

00:18:17.845 --> 00:18:18.970
And you can read them here.

00:18:18.970 --> 00:18:20.320
There in your notes.

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:22.710
Lead with credibility
and caring.

00:18:22.710 --> 00:18:26.110
Hire and training for relational
competence, and not just

00:18:26.110 --> 00:18:27.670
for other factors.

00:18:27.670 --> 00:18:29.415
Bridging the work-family divide.

00:18:29.415 --> 00:18:30.790
Recognizing that
that's something

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:32.560
important for employees.

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:33.970
Measuring performance broadly.

00:18:33.970 --> 00:18:36.790
Making unions your partners.

00:18:36.790 --> 00:18:39.520
Building relationships
with your suppliers.

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:42.850
Keeping jobs flexible
at the boundaries.

00:18:42.850 --> 00:18:44.910
In addition, creating
boundaries spanners

00:18:44.910 --> 00:18:47.500
who are crossing different
parts of the organization.

00:18:47.500 --> 00:18:50.540
Using conflicts to
build relationships

00:18:50.540 --> 00:18:51.640
and to learn and grow.

00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:54.610
And investing in
front line leadership.

00:18:54.610 --> 00:18:57.310
That's not the leadership at
the C-suite of the organization,

00:18:57.310 --> 00:19:01.750
but those who are right on the
front lines of, for Southwest,

00:19:01.750 --> 00:19:04.090
maintaining your planes,
manning the gates

00:19:04.090 --> 00:19:07.120
and interacting with
customers and so on.

00:19:07.120 --> 00:19:10.450
And then the outcomes that
professor Hoffer Gittell

00:19:10.450 --> 00:19:14.930
found relational coordination
leads to is higher reliability.

00:19:14.930 --> 00:19:17.410
This was judged for airlines
by better on time performance

00:19:17.410 --> 00:19:18.880
and fewer lost bags.

00:19:18.880 --> 00:19:22.630
As well as greater customer
satisfaction and shorter

00:19:22.630 --> 00:19:25.690
turnaround time, which is
really important in an industry

00:19:25.690 --> 00:19:28.780
like air transportation, where
you have very expensive capital

00:19:28.780 --> 00:19:29.547
assets.

00:19:29.547 --> 00:19:31.630
And the more time they're
used, the greater return

00:19:31.630 --> 00:19:32.980
you're getting on
them, and the more time

00:19:32.980 --> 00:19:35.522
they sit idle at the gate while
they're waiting to be cleaned

00:19:35.522 --> 00:19:37.900
and you're offloading
and onloading passengers,

00:19:37.900 --> 00:19:41.770
it's not generating any
revenue for the organization.

00:19:41.770 --> 00:19:44.980
To turn to an example
from health care,

00:19:44.980 --> 00:19:48.985
this reflects back on that
chart that I showed you

00:19:48.985 --> 00:19:51.430
two slides ago with
the coordination

00:19:51.430 --> 00:19:54.690
between relational
coordination and performance.

00:19:54.690 --> 00:19:57.280
It hypothesizes that
if we were able to make

00:19:57.280 --> 00:20:01.000
a 100% improvement in
various work practices

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:03.550
that underlie relational
coordination in hospitals-- so

00:20:03.550 --> 00:20:08.290
if we were to double our measure
of relational coordination

00:20:08.290 --> 00:20:10.810
our improvement in
these work practices--

00:20:10.810 --> 00:20:13.870
we would have an
almost 50% increase

00:20:13.870 --> 00:20:15.790
in relational coordination,
which would then

00:20:15.790 --> 00:20:19.060
lead to significant increases
in patient satisfaction

00:20:19.060 --> 00:20:21.430
and decreases in
the length of stay.

00:20:21.430 --> 00:20:23.440
Which are all very good
things because these

00:20:23.440 --> 00:20:26.380
are what hospitals and health
care settings tend to measure,

00:20:26.380 --> 00:20:28.410
right health care folks?

00:20:28.410 --> 00:20:29.880
You're probably
measured on those.

00:20:29.880 --> 00:20:31.600
It's also interesting
to me to note that,

00:20:31.600 --> 00:20:34.480
well, just because we increase
our relational coordination

00:20:34.480 --> 00:20:36.206
doesn't necessarily
mean we're going

00:20:36.206 --> 00:20:39.400
to increase people's freedom
from pain or their mobility.

00:20:39.400 --> 00:20:41.170
This is a joint unit
that was studied

00:20:41.170 --> 00:20:43.378
in this particular focus area.

00:20:43.378 --> 00:20:44.920
Because these are
really more related

00:20:44.920 --> 00:20:46.795
to the types of treatment
that you're giving,

00:20:46.795 --> 00:20:50.560
but these are elements that
are really being measured

00:20:50.560 --> 00:20:53.510
in the hospital setting.

00:20:53.510 --> 00:20:56.350
So just to conclude our
discussion about Southwest

00:20:56.350 --> 00:20:58.852
and the power of workforce
productivity, some

00:20:58.852 --> 00:21:00.310
of the benefits
that you see, we've

00:21:00.310 --> 00:21:02.380
got bigger revenues
that are generated

00:21:02.380 --> 00:21:04.420
from not only
satisfied customers

00:21:04.420 --> 00:21:07.110
but better utilized
capital assets here.

00:21:07.110 --> 00:21:09.880
And we have reduced costs
from lower employee turnover.

00:21:09.880 --> 00:21:12.760
If they're productive and
satisfied and not having people

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:13.750
sit idle.

00:21:13.750 --> 00:21:15.400
Wasted human resources.

00:21:15.400 --> 00:21:17.870
It's a very bad thing.

00:21:17.870 --> 00:21:19.540
And lastly, increased
productivity leads

00:21:19.540 --> 00:21:21.040
to happy, satisfied
employees, which

00:21:21.040 --> 00:21:22.832
leads to more increased
productivity, which

00:21:22.832 --> 00:21:24.590
leads to more happy,
satisfied employees.

00:21:24.590 --> 00:21:25.930
A very virtuous circle.

00:21:29.450 --> 00:21:32.340
So now we'd like to turn from
our case example of Southwest

00:21:32.340 --> 00:21:35.430
and linking employee
satisfaction, essentially,

00:21:35.430 --> 00:21:40.560
and productivity to now
talking about working in teams

00:21:40.560 --> 00:21:44.545
and thinking about how teams
can better work together.

00:21:44.545 --> 00:21:46.920
And to start that off we want
to do some active learning.

00:21:46.920 --> 00:21:49.180
We're going to have
a class debate.

00:21:49.180 --> 00:21:50.730
So the objective
here is you're going

00:21:50.730 --> 00:21:53.490
to have a time
constraint, and you're

00:21:53.490 --> 00:21:56.120
going to have to articulate
a clear and concise message

00:21:56.120 --> 00:21:58.050
on one side of the
debate or the other.

00:21:58.050 --> 00:21:59.970
That's your overall objective.

00:21:59.970 --> 00:22:01.470
But while you're
doing that, we want

00:22:01.470 --> 00:22:04.980
you to observe a couple of
things about the team dynamics.

00:22:04.980 --> 00:22:07.560
We want you to think about
how differing viewpoints

00:22:07.560 --> 00:22:09.960
in your team affect their work.

00:22:09.960 --> 00:22:11.970
We want you think about
the processes used

00:22:11.970 --> 00:22:14.190
for your group decision making.

00:22:14.190 --> 00:22:17.730
And lastly, we want you to think
about how completing the task

00:22:17.730 --> 00:22:20.160
depends upon the
personal feelings

00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:22.632
of your group and the process.

00:22:22.632 --> 00:22:24.090
So there's two
things you're doing.

00:22:24.090 --> 00:22:27.578
One is you're making
this argument.

00:22:27.578 --> 00:22:30.120
And two, you're stepping back
and observing the whole process

00:22:30.120 --> 00:22:33.730
while it happens and taking
notes on both of those.

00:22:33.730 --> 00:22:36.730
All right so here is our debate.

00:22:36.730 --> 00:22:38.190
So the early bird
may get the worm,

00:22:38.190 --> 00:22:41.790
but it's a second mouse
that gets the cheese.

00:22:41.790 --> 00:22:44.720
So the birds proposition
here in this debate,

00:22:44.720 --> 00:22:48.150
putting it in a Lean context,
early adopters of lean thinking

00:22:48.150 --> 00:22:50.828
gain the greatest
competitive advantage.

00:22:50.828 --> 00:22:52.620
But then there's another
side of the debate

00:22:52.620 --> 00:22:53.870
that goes something like this.

00:22:53.870 --> 00:22:56.938
That the second followers,
people who are not the first,

00:22:56.938 --> 00:22:58.480
the second followers
of lean thinking

00:22:58.480 --> 00:23:01.630
gain the greatest
competitive advantage.

00:23:01.630 --> 00:23:03.660
So either of those
points could be true.

00:23:03.660 --> 00:23:05.490
