00:34:59.716 --> 00:35:01.770
So you might have had
a little more conflict.

00:35:01.770 --> 00:35:03.940
Whereas here, since we
were given our conclusion,

00:35:03.940 --> 00:35:06.310
everyone was just
trying to quickly find

00:35:06.310 --> 00:35:09.620
ways to support that
conclusion together.

00:35:09.620 --> 00:35:11.370
ANNALISA WEIGEL: And
this table over here?

00:35:11.370 --> 00:35:13.620
Where you guys had an even
split of yellows and greens

00:35:13.620 --> 00:35:15.860
in your personal votes?

00:35:15.860 --> 00:35:16.970
AUDIENCE: No.

00:35:16.970 --> 00:35:18.504
AUDIENCE: We were all yellow.

00:35:18.504 --> 00:35:20.662
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:20.662 --> 00:35:23.120
AUDIENCE: We worked so well
together that we were actually,

00:35:23.120 --> 00:35:24.120
truly, convinced.

00:35:28.055 --> 00:35:29.180
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Excellent.

00:35:29.180 --> 00:35:34.170
Let's talk about the
process that you used.

00:35:34.170 --> 00:35:37.100
We just had a big lecture on
process before this, right?

00:35:37.100 --> 00:35:38.930
And seeing life as a process.

00:35:38.930 --> 00:35:41.630
What process did you use?

00:35:41.630 --> 00:35:43.550
AUDIENCE: We had a good process.

00:35:43.550 --> 00:35:46.370
I mean, everyone had to give
their opinion initially.

00:35:46.370 --> 00:35:50.370
We had input from everyone
before coming to a consensus.

00:35:50.370 --> 00:35:52.280
So it wasn't like
someone just came up

00:35:52.280 --> 00:35:53.330
with the final solution.

00:35:53.330 --> 00:35:56.520
I mean, we have to listen to
everybody's point of view.

00:35:56.520 --> 00:35:58.760
And maybe because our
group is small, maybe

00:35:58.760 --> 00:36:01.250
it was more effective,
we were able to come

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:04.280
to a very quick conclusion
based on different input

00:36:04.280 --> 00:36:04.928
from everyone.

00:36:04.928 --> 00:36:06.845
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Other
reflections on process?

00:36:11.430 --> 00:36:13.560
AUDIENCE: I guess it was
not explicitly delineated,

00:36:13.560 --> 00:36:16.950
but we split up our time into
three different sections.

00:36:16.950 --> 00:36:21.240
One was just anyone who just
chimed in with their own answer

00:36:21.240 --> 00:36:22.250
supporting the case.

00:36:22.250 --> 00:36:25.290
Two was looking and
anticipating rebuttals,

00:36:25.290 --> 00:36:27.227
and three was just
writing it all down.

00:36:27.227 --> 00:36:28.352
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Excellent.

00:36:28.352 --> 00:36:32.080
And did you come up with
a written statement?

00:36:32.080 --> 00:36:34.510
AUDIENCE: Yeah, we did.

00:36:34.510 --> 00:36:35.742
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Excellent.

00:36:35.742 --> 00:36:39.467
[CLASS TWITTERING]

00:36:39.467 --> 00:36:41.300
ANNALISA WEIGEL: How
about your satisfaction

00:36:41.300 --> 00:36:43.700
with the team outcomes.

00:36:43.700 --> 00:36:48.816
Anybody unsatisfied or
satisfied with the team outcome?

00:36:48.816 --> 00:36:50.528
I'm going to hazard
a guess on balance.

00:36:50.528 --> 00:36:52.070
People seemed
satisfied because there

00:36:52.070 --> 00:36:53.810
wasn't a lot of
storming out of the room

00:36:53.810 --> 00:36:55.070
and yelling and shouting.

00:36:55.070 --> 00:36:59.210
But, if you had any complaints
however small about your team

00:36:59.210 --> 00:37:00.200
outcomes.

00:37:00.200 --> 00:37:01.580
If you wanted to voice that.

00:37:01.580 --> 00:37:02.200
AUDIENCE: Don't get me wrong.

00:37:02.200 --> 00:37:03.992
We were mice, but by
the time we were done,

00:37:03.992 --> 00:37:07.243
we were all pretty much
agreed on the bird view.

00:37:07.243 --> 00:37:09.410
AUDIENCE: I think we started
out with the bird view.

00:37:09.410 --> 00:37:11.230
We forced ourselves to
go to our mice view,

00:37:11.230 --> 00:37:12.855
and then we came
back to bird view.

00:37:12.855 --> 00:37:14.480
AUDIENCE: Because as
soon as we started

00:37:14.480 --> 00:37:16.733
talking about a rebuttal
we realized, yeah.

00:37:18.912 --> 00:37:20.870
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Which
is why good debate teams

00:37:20.870 --> 00:37:23.300
work on their rebuttals a lot.

00:37:23.300 --> 00:37:26.060
OK so let's use this
exercise then to jump off

00:37:26.060 --> 00:37:29.240
into our last segment of
slides here in our people

00:37:29.240 --> 00:37:34.010
module focusing on team
elements and team skills.

00:37:34.010 --> 00:37:36.530
And this chart is our
transition to just remind us how

00:37:36.530 --> 00:37:38.300
people are the heart of Lean.

00:37:38.300 --> 00:37:41.540
Because we have the tasks, which
are what the people are doing.

00:37:41.540 --> 00:37:45.190
And you all just had a
task in your exercise.

00:37:45.190 --> 00:37:47.315
The processes are how people
are doing their tasks.

00:37:47.315 --> 00:37:49.482
And we talked about what
your process may or may not

00:37:49.482 --> 00:37:49.982
have been.

00:37:49.982 --> 00:37:51.232
But it's all about the people.

00:37:51.232 --> 00:37:52.640
The people are doing the tasks.

00:37:52.640 --> 00:37:54.170
The people are
doing the process.

00:37:54.170 --> 00:37:57.470
And they set within various
organization structures

00:37:57.470 --> 00:38:00.020
that are what enable them to
do their processes and tasks.

00:38:00.020 --> 00:38:02.270
And that's all embedded in
a particular organization's

00:38:02.270 --> 00:38:08.690
culture, which has attributes
about it that further influence

00:38:08.690 --> 00:38:13.410
and enable a person's ability
to do their tasks and processes.

00:38:13.410 --> 00:38:15.980
Many of the work that
people do are in teams

00:38:15.980 --> 00:38:17.480
and they're collaborating.

00:38:17.480 --> 00:38:20.300
And there's really three
elements of collaboration.

00:38:20.300 --> 00:38:22.670
There's not just the
thing you're doing,

00:38:22.670 --> 00:38:24.830
but there's how you're
doing it and then there's

00:38:24.830 --> 00:38:28.718
this thing we call affect, which
is the feelings about the work.

00:38:28.718 --> 00:38:30.260
And this is what
the people bring to.

00:38:30.260 --> 00:38:32.720
And it's based on your
prior experiences.

00:38:32.720 --> 00:38:34.220
It's based on the
culture that you

00:38:34.220 --> 00:38:38.300
sit in, organizational,
national, ethnic, et cetera,

00:38:38.300 --> 00:38:41.033
on your own biases that you
bring to what you're doing.

00:38:41.033 --> 00:38:42.950
And it's also based on
your current experience

00:38:42.950 --> 00:38:44.180
and where you are.

00:38:44.180 --> 00:38:47.930
And it's both the process
as well as the feelings

00:38:47.930 --> 00:38:49.760
or the affect that
are supporting

00:38:49.760 --> 00:38:52.400
the task actually getting done.

00:38:52.400 --> 00:38:54.080
When you're
collaborating in teams,

00:38:54.080 --> 00:38:56.780
and you're bringing all these
elements together of process,

00:38:56.780 --> 00:38:58.190
task, and affect.

00:38:58.190 --> 00:39:00.320
There's a lot of benefits
to collaboration.

00:39:00.320 --> 00:39:03.020
You get-- I think most of you
would recognize these-- you get

00:39:03.020 --> 00:39:06.230
more ideas, new ideas,
multiple areas of expertise

00:39:06.230 --> 00:39:08.030
to bring to bear on the problem.

00:39:08.030 --> 00:39:09.320
Work is shared.

00:39:09.320 --> 00:39:11.600
It should result in some
stronger problem solving

00:39:11.600 --> 00:39:14.540
abilities and should improve
things like design work

00:39:14.540 --> 00:39:17.150
and other kind of
creative tasks.

00:39:17.150 --> 00:39:20.900
But there's also a lot of
challenges that are involved

00:39:20.900 --> 00:39:22.130
in collaborating with teams.

00:39:22.130 --> 00:39:23.672
And I'm sure you've
all run into some

00:39:23.672 --> 00:39:26.173
of those over the course of
your school and work time.

00:39:26.173 --> 00:39:27.590
So what are some
of the challenges

00:39:27.590 --> 00:39:31.770
you run into when you're
trying to collaborate?

00:39:31.770 --> 00:39:33.660
AUDIENCE: The workload
isn't shared evenly.

00:39:33.660 --> 00:39:35.702
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Not shared
evenly in a workload.

00:39:35.702 --> 00:39:36.610
What else?

00:39:36.610 --> 00:39:39.400
AUDIENCE: I think diversity
can bring new ideas.

00:39:39.400 --> 00:39:42.040
But if our group size
was larger, I mean,

00:39:42.040 --> 00:39:45.010
it's hard to accommodate
everyone's ideas.

00:39:45.010 --> 00:39:47.810
So somebody might
view that, oh my ideas

00:39:47.810 --> 00:39:50.390
didn't get into the process.

00:39:50.390 --> 00:39:52.900
ANNALISA WEIGEL: So it can
be inefficient and unwieldy?

00:39:52.900 --> 00:39:53.990
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:39:53.990 --> 00:39:55.407
AUDIENCE: It takes
time to develop

00:39:55.407 --> 00:39:56.948
a consensus in a big team.

00:39:56.948 --> 00:39:58.490
ANNALISA WEIGEL:
More time consuming.

00:40:01.110 --> 00:40:01.610
Yes.

00:40:01.610 --> 00:40:03.830
AUDIENCE: We were talking
about how as we go in,

00:40:03.830 --> 00:40:07.400
the people that we're working
with may not be skilled.

00:40:07.400 --> 00:40:10.010
May not know how to work
in this sort of model.

00:40:10.010 --> 00:40:12.260
That they're used to just
being told what to do.

00:40:12.260 --> 00:40:14.120
I see that on a micro
level with patients,

00:40:14.120 --> 00:40:17.960
but also if you try
and ask your staff

00:40:17.960 --> 00:40:22.160
to be more of a contributor,
and be more responsible

00:40:22.160 --> 00:40:23.940
and also take on
more credit, they

00:40:23.940 --> 00:40:25.607
may be like, what are
you talking about?

00:40:25.607 --> 00:40:27.620
I punch in, I punch out.

00:40:27.620 --> 00:40:29.280
I'm not a member in that way.

00:40:29.280 --> 00:40:30.700
So you have to retrain them.

00:40:30.700 --> 00:40:31.340
ANNALISA WEIGEL:
People just may not

00:40:31.340 --> 00:40:34.130
have the skills to collaborate
in teams that they need.

00:40:34.130 --> 00:40:37.833
Either by training or
just by expectations.

00:40:37.833 --> 00:40:39.500
These are some of the
common challenges.

00:40:39.500 --> 00:40:42.650
I'll just list for you on
the rest of the slide ones

00:40:42.650 --> 00:40:44.930
that we think are
prominent as well.

00:40:44.930 --> 00:40:46.517
Different goals and values.

00:40:46.517 --> 00:40:48.350
We just talked about
not being skilled in it

00:40:48.350 --> 00:40:49.790
or practiced in it.

00:40:49.790 --> 00:40:51.680
Sometimes you run
into ego issues

00:40:51.680 --> 00:40:54.350
and people are defensive
about their particular work

00:40:54.350 --> 00:40:55.950
or their ideas.

00:40:55.950 --> 00:40:59.000
Their preconceived notions that
get in the way of teamwork.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:00.710
And then there's
differing work styles

00:41:00.710 --> 00:41:02.377
that you try to bring
together in a team

00:41:02.377 --> 00:41:03.890
and that can be
counterproductive

00:41:03.890 --> 00:41:05.240
to your efficiency.

00:41:05.240 --> 00:41:07.790
Or maybe somebody worked in
a bad team situation before

00:41:07.790 --> 00:41:11.000
and that's just really hindering
their ability to work together

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:13.153
productively in future teams.

00:41:13.153 --> 00:41:14.570
So then, with all
these challenges

00:41:14.570 --> 00:41:16.370
how do you meet them?

00:41:16.370 --> 00:41:17.850
What are some of your thoughts?

00:41:17.850 --> 00:41:20.840
AUDIENCE: I think
setting out ahead of time

00:41:20.840 --> 00:41:23.220
what the expectations
of teamwork

00:41:23.220 --> 00:41:26.900
are, and just kind
of lay out for people

00:41:26.900 --> 00:41:29.788
how do you work with a team?

00:41:29.788 --> 00:41:31.270
Like respect others.

00:41:31.270 --> 00:41:33.565
Listen first, speak later.

00:41:33.565 --> 00:41:34.375
Things like that.

00:41:34.375 --> 00:41:35.500
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Excellent.

00:41:35.500 --> 00:41:38.395
So clear rules and education.

00:41:38.395 --> 00:41:40.270
AUDIENCE: I think shared
knowledge and shared

00:41:40.270 --> 00:41:44.140
goals can add a lot to the
relational coordination,

00:41:44.140 --> 00:41:47.680
because this is how you
share your goals with others

00:41:47.680 --> 00:41:50.580
and try to convince them to
come to the same conclusion.

00:41:50.580 --> 00:41:53.775
Otherwise, I mean, everyone
feels that I had my own ideas.

00:41:57.810 --> 00:41:59.190
AUDIENCE: Something important.

00:41:59.190 --> 00:42:01.410
The diagrams you always
show about collaboration,

00:42:01.410 --> 00:42:04.020
is always-- the puzzle pieces
always fit perfectly, which

00:42:04.020 --> 00:42:06.320
I think is a misrepresentation.

00:42:06.320 --> 00:42:09.220
You have to accept that puzzle
pieces won't fit perfectly,

00:42:09.220 --> 00:42:12.570
and there's someone who's going
to make a decision in the end.

00:42:12.570 --> 00:42:14.510
And if there is a culture
of mutual respect,

00:42:14.510 --> 00:42:16.760
the person making the decision
will respect the people

00:42:16.760 --> 00:42:19.780
that brought in
suggestions and vice versa

00:42:19.780 --> 00:42:23.700
and that's just
the nature of life.

00:42:23.700 --> 00:42:27.950
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Establishing
that expectation is important.

00:42:27.950 --> 00:42:29.560
AUDIENCE: Things
like ongoing training

00:42:29.560 --> 00:42:32.200
and starting off
with something small

00:42:32.200 --> 00:42:37.390
that you can have an obvious,
tangible result with guaranteed

00:42:37.390 --> 00:42:38.000
success.

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:41.060
So that they can learn the
process and feel good about it.

00:42:41.060 --> 00:42:45.820
And then keep continuously
doing ongoing training over time

00:42:45.820 --> 00:42:52.320
to improve their ability
to do it and remind them.

00:42:52.320 --> 00:42:53.670
ANNALISA WEIGEL: Excellent.

00:42:53.670 --> 00:42:56.010
Again really excellent ideas.

00:42:56.010 --> 00:42:58.527
Let me spell out
some others, some

00:42:58.527 --> 00:43:00.360
that are duplicate of
what we just discussed

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:02.070
and some which are new.

00:43:02.070 --> 00:43:04.110
So long the lines are
trying to make it explicit

00:43:04.110 --> 00:43:06.540
and trying to train people
and set expectations,

00:43:06.540 --> 00:43:09.250
you may want to try to do those
also in writing and not just

00:43:09.250 --> 00:43:09.750
verbally.

00:43:09.750 --> 00:43:11.167
Sometimes seeing
things in writing

00:43:11.167 --> 00:43:14.880
can really help people
understand what's going on.

00:43:14.880 --> 00:43:17.010
Considering alternate
ideas or solutions

00:43:17.010 --> 00:43:18.990
and not jumping to
consensus prematurely

00:43:18.990 --> 00:43:22.590
can be one way to meet the
challenges of collaboration.

00:43:22.590 --> 00:43:25.020
Paying careful attention to
process is really important.

00:43:25.020 --> 00:43:28.770
If people understand the process
is very clear and very fair,

00:43:28.770 --> 00:43:31.500
then when they express opinions
that are counter to what

00:43:31.500 --> 00:43:33.390
the rest of the group
does want to do,

00:43:33.390 --> 00:43:34.740
and the group goes in
a different direction,

00:43:34.740 --> 00:43:36.490
at least that person
has felt that they've

00:43:36.490 --> 00:43:41.250
had their due process and they
haven't been short changed.

00:43:41.250 --> 00:43:43.860
The next point voicing
disagreements constructively,

00:43:43.860 --> 00:43:46.320
directly, and explicitly
is really important.

00:43:46.320 --> 00:43:48.270
Because you're not
all going to agree

00:43:48.270 --> 00:43:50.930
except for certain groups in
this particular exercise, where

00:43:50.930 --> 00:43:52.380
you've all coalesced
on a certain point.

00:43:52.380 --> 00:43:53.815
But in your work
environments, you

00:43:53.815 --> 00:43:55.565
are going to have times
when you disagree.

00:43:55.565 --> 00:43:57.280
And learning how to
do that productively.

00:43:57.280 --> 00:43:59.510
So that you're focusing
just on the disagreement

00:43:59.510 --> 00:44:02.250
not on the person that you're
having that disagreement with

00:44:02.250 --> 00:44:05.880
will help you get to a
solution more productively.

00:44:05.880 --> 00:44:09.630
Lastly, give positive feedback
directly and explicitly too.

00:44:09.630 --> 00:44:12.150
So how many times a day
do you say to a colleague,

00:44:12.150 --> 00:44:13.712
that was a great job.

00:44:13.712 --> 00:44:16.170
And then think of how many
times you make critical comments

00:44:16.170 --> 00:44:18.570
about a peer's or colleague's
work or suggestions

00:44:18.570 --> 00:44:19.840
for improvement.

00:44:19.840 --> 00:44:22.590
Especially at MIT,
we have a reputation

00:44:22.590 --> 00:44:25.170
for being a praise
free zone here.

00:44:25.170 --> 00:44:28.170
Lots of criticism.

00:44:28.170 --> 00:44:29.550
It's very important
that you also

00:44:29.550 --> 00:44:31.843
reinforce the positives
in collaboration,

00:44:31.843 --> 00:44:34.260
because that's going to foster
the team being able to work

00:44:34.260 --> 00:44:35.230
productively together.

00:44:38.670 --> 00:44:40.360
Now in organizations,
you're going

00:44:40.360 --> 00:44:43.260
to find many entities
are organized

00:44:43.260 --> 00:44:44.930
in teams of various sorts.

00:44:44.930 --> 00:44:46.800
And this diagram
helps orient you

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:49.200
to some of the previous as
well as current structures

00:44:49.200 --> 00:44:54.000
that we find in a lot of the
complex engineering system

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:56.520
kinds of industries.

00:44:56.520 --> 00:45:00.320
Usually, the organization
is broken down functionally.

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:01.890
There may be a design
function, there

00:45:01.890 --> 00:45:03.390
may be an operations
function, there

00:45:03.390 --> 00:45:05.580
may be a maintenance function.

00:45:05.580 --> 00:45:07.980
Or it may be a structure
function, a thermal function,

00:45:07.980 --> 00:45:09.750
and so on.

00:45:09.750 --> 00:45:13.028
And it used to be that
groups worked independently,

00:45:13.028 --> 00:45:14.820
and whenever you had
yo collaborate somehow

00:45:14.820 --> 00:45:16.860
between, say, function
one and function two,

00:45:16.860 --> 00:45:19.740
the interface took place
between the top people.

00:45:19.740 --> 00:45:21.330
But it was usually
the folks down here

00:45:21.330 --> 00:45:23.070
who were doing all
the work and needed

00:45:23.070 --> 00:45:24.397
the answers from these people.

00:45:24.397 --> 00:45:26.730
But they had to work all the
way up through their bosses

00:45:26.730 --> 00:45:28.313
to communicate with
that person's boss

00:45:28.313 --> 00:45:30.170
to work all the way
down through the chain.

00:45:30.170 --> 00:45:33.180
So that's kind of the old style,
the way organizations worked.

00:45:33.180 --> 00:45:35.460
And then a couple
decades ago, we

00:45:35.460 --> 00:45:38.340
introduced the concept of
integrated product and process

00:45:38.340 --> 00:45:41.250
teams, which really took
essentially the folks doing

00:45:41.250 --> 00:45:44.070
the work down here and
put them into a team

00:45:44.070 --> 00:45:46.890
so the communication could
happen directly between people

00:45:46.890 --> 00:45:49.350
who were doing the tasks
and not really up and down

00:45:49.350 --> 00:45:50.820
a chain of communications.

00:45:50.820 --> 00:45:53.130
There, it really didn't
matter that this person knew

00:45:53.130 --> 00:45:54.180
what the question
was that they're

00:45:54.180 --> 00:45:55.520
asking had to be passed along.

00:45:55.520 --> 00:45:56.570
They're just relaying it.

00:45:56.570 --> 00:45:58.950
It's much better if you
can have direct interaction

00:45:58.950 --> 00:46:00.372
between people.

00:46:00.372 --> 00:46:02.080
So this kind of an
organization structure

00:46:02.080 --> 00:46:05.400
has helped increase the
effective communications

00:46:05.400 --> 00:46:08.190
and the ability for
teams to work together

00:46:08.190 --> 00:46:11.500
in these complex enterprises
that we see today.

00:46:11.500 --> 00:46:16.260
But being on an IPT
or an IPPT, you're

00:46:16.260 --> 00:46:19.530
now asking people who are in
this part of the organization

00:46:19.530 --> 00:46:23.700
to have teamwork and leadership
skills that they might not

00:46:23.700 --> 00:46:26.850
have needed to have in our
old kind of organization

00:46:26.850 --> 00:46:29.768
where the leadership was
largely done at the top.

00:46:29.768 --> 00:46:31.560
So this helps us
understand why introducing

00:46:31.560 --> 00:46:33.623
the concepts of
teamwork and leadership

00:46:33.623 --> 00:46:35.040
and developing
skills around those

00:46:35.040 --> 00:46:37.410
is really important to
do really from day one.

00:46:37.410 --> 00:46:39.030
When you join an
organization and not

00:46:39.030 --> 00:46:43.400
waiting until you get to be
at the top of that org chart.

00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:46.317
Now teams progress through a
number of different stages.

00:46:46.317 --> 00:46:48.150
And there is a lot of
literature about this,

00:46:48.150 --> 00:46:50.490
but in essence when you
first start out with a team

00:46:50.490 --> 00:46:52.865
there's a lot of challenges
we just discussed and working

00:46:52.865 --> 00:46:53.460
together.

00:46:53.460 --> 00:46:55.470
And teams take a
little while to grow

00:46:55.470 --> 00:46:57.180
from beginning teams
to what we'd really

00:46:57.180 --> 00:46:58.950
call high performance ones.

00:46:58.950 --> 00:47:01.050
And the degree of management
necessary for those

00:47:01.050 --> 00:47:03.630
decreases over time as we get
towards a more high performing

00:47:03.630 --> 00:47:04.293
team.

00:47:04.293 --> 00:47:06.210
And their empowerment
and ability to do things

00:47:06.210 --> 00:47:07.540
increases as well.

00:47:07.540 --> 00:47:09.480
We find that when we
look at high performing

00:47:09.480 --> 00:47:11.520
teams in a Lean
environment, they have

00:47:11.520 --> 00:47:12.860
these attributes about them.

00:47:12.860 --> 00:47:14.970
And we've mentioned
most of them so far.

00:47:14.970 --> 00:47:18.660
They have mutual respect
for all people and all jobs.

00:47:18.660 --> 00:47:21.100
They encourage contribution
by all the team members.

00:47:21.100 --> 00:47:24.660
We heard Claudio talk about
that in our tour today.

00:47:24.660 --> 00:47:26.730
Different opinions
are not only valued

00:47:26.730 --> 00:47:29.010
but they're sought
after and brought out.

00:47:29.010 --> 00:47:32.250
There is open and honest
communication and feedback.

00:47:32.250 --> 00:47:35.340
The goals of the
team are aligned.

00:47:35.340 --> 00:47:38.400
There is continuous improvement
of both the individuals

00:47:38.400 --> 00:47:39.540
and the team.

00:47:39.540 --> 00:47:41.730
Always seeking to
do a better job.

00:47:41.730 --> 00:47:44.040
And there is a high degree
of synergy and cooperation

00:47:44.040 --> 00:47:45.618
among the members.

00:47:45.618 --> 00:47:47.160
So if you're striving
to put together

00:47:47.160 --> 00:47:48.743
a team that is high
performing, you're

00:47:48.743 --> 00:47:52.442
really trying to work on these
seven particular attributes

00:47:52.442 --> 00:47:54.150
and try and increase
those for your team.

00:47:56.670 --> 00:48:00.300
So lastly we'll just
conclude with our chart here.

00:48:00.300 --> 00:48:03.210
People are the heart of Lean.

00:48:03.210 --> 00:48:04.620
With our shared
goals, our shared

00:48:04.620 --> 00:48:07.560
knowledge, mutual respect,
communication, teamwork,

00:48:07.560 --> 00:48:08.190
and leadership.

00:48:08.190 --> 00:48:13.208
All the hallmarks of a
high performing Lean team.

